deck_excerpt: Use synchro spam to turbo Quasar and Blazar (without Sorc or Needlefiber) + Draw into generic floodgates to shutdown opponent
deck_description:
Requirements(In Hand):
  1. Draconnet, Cynet Mining, Souleating Oviraptor, Fossil Dig, or Mathematician
  2. No more than one copy each of any of the combo cards that are run at two (Bulb, Steam, Doppel, Jet, Guardragon, Carbo)
This is one of the more consistent Quasar deck variants I have seen, and mathematically has an 80-85% chance to be able to start the combo. Combo:
  1. Pray you go first
  2. Make Ib with Draconnet/Oviraptor/Mathematician (Cynet searches Draconnet and Fossil searches Oviraptor)
  3. Ib searches World Legacy Guardragon
  4. World Legacy Guardragon revives the dragon tuner used to make Ib (Galaxy Serpent/Flamvell Guard)
  5. Link Ib and tuner into Reprodocus
  6. Ib SS World Chalice Guardragon to the zone Reprodocus points to
  7. Reprodocus changes Guardragon to Earth
  8. Link Reprodocus and Guardragon into Missus Radiant
  9. Banish Guardragon to SS the tuner
  10. Link tuner into Elpy
  11. Use Legacy to move Elpy under Radiant
  12. Elpy SS Omni Dragon Brotaur
  13. Brotaur target Radiant, add Ferret to hand
  14. Link everything on field into Saryuja (If possible, use any extender to get a 4th material)
  15. Saryuja SS Rescue Ferret
  16. Rest of the combo can be seen here: https://youtu.be/1xXTqjTp44w?t=37
  17. Use the draw power from Librarian + Magical Mallet to get Summon Limit, Imperial Order, ASF, and Ash in hand and floodgate your opponent
  18. Negate everything on their turn and hope they can't play through it (IDK if any decks can play through an Imperial Order, Summon Limit, summon negate, effect negate, and ashes but its still RNG what you draw)
  19. Attack twice with Quasar for game
Changes: There really isn't much to say, this deck is still in testing and the ratios could still be tweaked. The floodgates can be adjusted based on the meta and your opponent, and by no means are the ones in the deck the best floodgates. You can put any other good floodgates or extenders in there to improve the deck, and suggestions are welcome in the comments.

deck_description: This deck's main goal is to flood your field using Gilgamesh and Ragnarok to bring back D'Arc. The ideal hand is Swirl, Necro, Ragnarok and either Kepler or Contract with the Gate. To start the combo, fuse Swirl and Necro to make D'Arc using Swirl's effect, normal summon any low level D/D so you can use it and D'Arc to make Gilgamesh, use his effect to place Copernicus and Kepler in your pendulum zones and summon Ragnarok, use his effect to bring back D'Arc. After this depending on what you have leftover you can use Necro to summon another D'Arc or Ghengis, if you didn't use CwtG you can add a lamia to your hand and try for a synchro. Ghost is supposed to help with GY setup or returning the slimes from banishment if things go south. If Gilgamesh goes down, it's usually a good idea to summon Purple Armageddon with his effect.  P.S. This is probably the only "good" deck I will ever make.

deck_excerpt: PS4 game deck. Pendulum/Synchro summons and Scrap monsters, swarming as well as recycling cards from the GY.
deck_description: Hello! This deck is ripped straight from the PS4 game "Yu-Gi-Oh! Legacy of the Duelist." As of May 23, 2019, Reinforcement of the Army is still limited to 1 copy, so make sure to take two copies out if you download this deck. As you can probably tell, this deck could not possibly keep up with today's decks, but it is a great casual deck to play around with and introduces yourself to Pendulum summons, Synchro summons, and the Scrap archetype. The goal of this deck first is to swarm the field using Pendulum summons, and recycle your Scrap monsters via their own effects second. Most of the Scrap monsters have the effect of returning a Scrap monster from GY to your hand as long a Scrap monster on your field was destroyed by a Scrap card's effect.  Your key monsters are Scrap Golem and Synchro-monster Scrap Dragon. Scrap Golem can special summon a Scrap monster from the GY to either player's field which will feed into the overall Scrap strategy. Scrap Dragon is your easiest useful Synchro Monster to Synchro summon and allows you to destroy 1 card on your opponent's field in exchange for one card you control, which can also trigger other Scrap monster effects.  Your Field Spell, Scrap Factory, is the third vital piece to this Scrap strategy, boosting Scrap-monster ATK/DEF slightly as well as allowing you to special summon a Scrap monster from the deck if a Scrap monster is destroyed by any card effect, including your opponent's, except during the damage step.  This deck is not very good and in need of many tune-ups, but it's a great deck to get started with and will destroy all of your friends' decks at the lunch table 100% guaranteed 50% of the time.

deck_excerpt: Pure Sky Striker Control 2019 (Post April 2019 Banlist)
deck_description: Hey everyone, so I've been playing Sky Strikers since it's release and have had a lot of success with it. It's a very powerful deck and it is still even with Sky Striker Ace - Kagari at one, you just have to learn to manage your resources. The goal of the deck is to go first and achieve a lot of draw power using Engage and then setting up multiple interruptions/negates using spells like Widow Anchor, Shark Cannon, Eagle Booster, Called By The Grave etc to stun your opponent consistently until you completely out grind them. After testing this build for a while ever since the release of the April 2019 banlist, I think it is really solid and I am hoping you guys will use it and enjoy it as much as I have. I hope you guys will use it to win since I've had much success with this build I created from scratch. Thank god for Hercules Base because it allows you to recur Kagari back into your extra deck so you can use it a second time, its first effect is also very powerful in battle. Equipping it to a Shizuku and then attacking your opponent's lowered attack monsters to draw 2 cards is busted. The last note I want to make is that I added Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf because you can actually go into it with 2 fire monsters like Hiita and Kagari, or whatever 2 fire monsters you can get. Link summoning Hiita and then using her effect to special summon a fire monster from your opponent's graveyard is normally the best way. The idea is to special summon a monster to the zone Sunlight Wolf points to below and use its effect to add back Kagari. This is an alternate option just in case you've already burned Hercules Base and the grind game is crucial. I love this as well because I play Ghost Cherries in the side deck because Sunlight Wolf is a Cherries target as well, and you can use Cherries for the mirror match. I hope you guys enjoy the deck and stick around for more!

deck_excerpt: Its allows you to Summon Ghostrick Angel of Mischief for the win.
deck_description:
Deck Created By: Big Crunch (Deck Inspiration: Tag Partner from Percy some time ago) Main Goal: Summon Ghostrick Angel of Mischief using Number 69: Heraldry Crest. How to Accomplish: Use the monsters to swarm the field. (Info Below)   Monsters
  • Legendary Six Samurai - Kageki - First turn Summon that allows you to Summon another Six Samurai. It can also be a discard.
  • Secret Six Samurai - Kizaru - Card that searches different Six Samurai cards with different Attribute when Special Summoned. Use it as much as possible.
  • Legendary Six Samurai - Kizan - A card that can be Special Summoned when you control another Six Samurai monster. Use it as much as possible.
  • Legendary Six Samurai - Mizuho - A card that can be Special Summon if you control Shinai. If you have the other monster, use it as much as you can.
  • Legendary Six Samurai - Shinai - A card that can be Special Summon if you control Muziho. If you have the other monster, use it as much as you can.
  • Grandmaster of the Six Samurai - A card that can be Special Summon if you control another Six Samurai monster . Use it carefully.
  • Secret Six Samurai - Hatsune - This card can banish 2 unimportant Six Samurai monsters to summon a Six Samurai monster that is useful in the situation.
Spells
  • Reinforcement of the Army - A Warrior Monster searcher. It helps you depends on the situation.
  • Monster Reborn - Revive a monster that you need for the combo or a top-deck card.
  • World Legacy Succession - If you have a Link monster, you can do a Monster Reborn like effect.
  • D.D.R. - Different Dimension Reincarnation - If your needed piece is banished, if you have a discard, you can use this card to grab that card. It is also an Equip card that Isolde can send to GY.
  • Living Fossil - Grab a Level 4 or lower monster from the Graveyard for combo continuation. It is also an Equip card that Isolde can send to GY.
  • Overdone Burial - It can summon a monster from the Graveyard that is lower level than your discard. It is also an Equip card that Isolde can send to GY.
  • Autonomous Action Unit - You can use this card if your opponent has a monster in the GY you can use, or you can revive a monster that can help you. It is also an Equip card that Isolde can send to GY.
  • One Day of Piece - A draw card that thins your deck, and prevents damage.
  • Upstart Goblin - A draw card that thins your deck.
  • Shien's Smoke Signal - A card that searches a Level 3 or lower Six Samurai monster from your deck.
  • Cunning of the Six Samurai - It allows you to switch a Six Samurai monster on a field to a Six Samurai monster from the Graveyard. It helps depends on the situation.
  • Gateway of the Six - It allows you to grab a Six Samurai monster from the Deck or Graveyard using your Bushido Counters (This card is very important. Don't lose it).
  • Shien's Dojo - It allows you to Summon a Six Samurai monster from your Deck. It's also a Bushido Counter generator for Gateway to use.
  • Six Samurai United. It allows you to draw card depending on its Bushido Counter. It's also a Bushido Counter generator for Gateway to use.
  • Overlay Regen - It allows you to attach the card to any XYZ monster you choose.
  Extra Deck Cards
  • Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights - Its a Link card that can grab you a free discard card and it can send Equips to the Graveyard to summon a Level 3-4 Warrior-Monster.
  • Great General of the Six Samurai - Its a Link card that can grab you a Bushido card depending on the situation. It is also a Bushido Counter generator for Gateway to use.
  • Number 75: Bamboozling Gossip Shadow - Its the XYZ monster that will give you extra materials to Number 69.
  • Number 69: Heraldry Crest - Its the first XYZ monster to be summoned. Its the XYZ monster that will copy the effect of Ghostrick Allucard.
  • Ghostrick Alucard - Its the XYZ monster that will be targeted for Number 69's effect.
  • Saryuja Skull Dread - Its a Link monster that allows you to adjust your draw a card and return cards from the deck. It can also Special Summon a monster from your hand.
  • Number 60: Dugales of Forgotten Time - Its an XYZ monster that allows you to draw cards or Special Summon a monster from your Graveyard.
  • Ghostrick Angel of Mischief - Its the XYZ monster that will be summoned by  Number 69. The card needs to have exactly 10 materials to activate its Win Condition.
  The main problem of this is that it is that the opponent can negate an important card piece that will prevent you from achieving the goal. The starting hand can also be a problem for executing the combo. You can add additional Extra Deck monsters of your choosing depends on your choice. Replay Example: http://www.mediafire.com/file/c72ogcy4i4iob4j/Mischief_FTK.yrp/file Download it and watch it on Percy. I used this deck on an opponent. This will give you a bit of an idea of how the deck works.

deck_excerpt: A deck that uses minimum effort to capitalize on the opponent's Solitaire plays. Force your opponent to play for you while you reap the benefits!
deck_description: This deck looks like a Graydle deck at a passing glance, but it is actually designed to capitalize on the opponent's plays while using as few resources as possible. The harder the opponent plays, the better this deck performs. You will note that the Side Deck has 15 cards of Kaiju support, and the Main Deck has 15 Graydle cards. These are meant to be interchanged to fully combat the biggest threats in the current meta. Either configuration is good for the Main Deck. I just chose Graydle for my personal preference. The Extra Deck has a pretty standard Knightmare inclusion. Graydle Dragon is good for the Archetype. Link Spider has good usage with Black Garden on board. Dhampir Vampire Sheridan is really easily accessed in full swing, and he allows for easy victory set-up. Destroy an opponent's Monster with his effect, take said Monster, and then use Sheridan and another monster to Link Summon a Knightmare and further destroy the opponent's board. It is very possible to get 2 Sheridan in one turn to set up an OTK. Borreload Dragon and Saryuja Skull Dread are easy Link-4 Monsters that you will want almost any time you can get them. Chimeratech Fortress Dragon is in the deck because... who doesn't want a free win against a popular deck? Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend is easily accessed with Graydle Slime, Graydle Slime Jr. and any other Graydle Monster. I have also gotten him out by taken control of an opponent's tuner and using Rose Tokens. At the end of the day, though, the Extra Deck is meant to throw away opponent's Monsters that would otherwise return to their control at the end of the turn. Link Summoning has made the core Main Deck very versatile. 9 of the 40 cards in the Main Deck are Spell Cards that take the opponent's Monster until the end of the turn with various restrictions/costs. Creature Swap is great for getting past "Cannot be targeted..." and "Unaffected by..." Monsters that would otherwise be problematic. Upstart Goblin and Contract with Don Thousand are both meant to draw into the deck. The latter gives insight on the opponent's hand and could force them to play their spells at inconvenient times (or not summon). The 1000 LP cost could also put you into the OTK zone at opportune times. ** Edited for L/F list changes** Black Garden + Remove Brainwashing allows for incredible laddering.
https://youtu.be/JGO5ZqaVVXU

deck_excerpt: Goal is to Synchro summon as quickly as possible with use of the spells and the effects of your monsters and Synchrons.
deck_description: Each card explained: -Junk Synchron: The staple of this deck. Every card in the deck is built around this guy. Your goal is to get him out on the playing field ASAP with supporting monsters to bring out any of the Synchros you see fit. -Quickdraw Synchron: The second staple of the deck. Quickdraw is what will allow you to pull out the Warrior cards that aren't Junk Warrior. It's effect also makes it easier to activate Junk Synchron's effect when you normal summon it, as you'll be discarding a card to special summon Quickdraw.(You generally never tribute for it) -Level Eater: This guy is perfect for increasing Junk Warrior's attack when you summon it, and it also works wonders paired with Quickdraw to open up more Synchro choices, even allowing you to summon Junk Warrior with Quickdraw. -Synchron Explorer: Basically has the reverse effect of Junk Synchron. Whenever you normal summon it, you can pull Junk or Quickdraw from your graveyard for easier Synchro summons. -Salvage Warrior: This is the only monster you'll be tribute summoning, and for good reason too. Whenever you can get him out, you should be doing so, as he'll enable some of the higher level synchro summons with Junk Synchron such as Stardust Dragon or Junk Destroyer. -Mystic Tomato: Mystic Tomato is only here so you can pull out Junk Synchron with more ease. -Junk Servant: Pairs excellently with Junk Synchron, as whenever you have Junk Synchron out on the field, you get to freely summon him and you can then Synchro summon any level 7 Synchro immediately. -Junk Blader: This guy is here simply to help out with pulling Junk Servant out, aiding in Synchro summoning, and can serve as a great starter monster due to it's 1800 attack. -Quillbolt Hedgehog: Almost a necessity to use in a Synchron deck due to it's effect, and pairs the best with Junk Synchron in particular. He helps pull out Junk Warrior in a snap.  -Mystical Space Typhoon: This deck lacks punishing spells/traps and gets rolled by stall decks that run Swords of Revealing Light, so this card will help relieve some of that pressure, and plus, it's always a good card to have in any deck. -Raigeki: You can replace this with Dark Hole if you want, but this is to pull the playing field in your favor if your opponent manages to get the upper hand. -Reinforcement of the Army: This card should almost solely be used to bring out Junk Synchron, but there's no harm in pulling out Blader or Servant. -Swords of Revealing Light: Simply here for some extra protection, that never hurts to have. -The Warrior Returning Alive: Allows you to continually reuse Junk Synchron for multiple Synchro summons. -Tuning: The most important Spell you have, you'll be able to freely bring in Quickdraw or Junk thanks to it, and when bringing out Junk, you have the potential to get a card like Quillbolt or Explorer sent to your graveyard from the top of your deck for even easier Synchro summoning. -Battleguard Howling: Similar to Swords, this is another protection card, and this one actually bites your opponent back. Helps keep your Warriors alive as well. -Call of the Haunted: Pretty self-explanatory, allows you to reuse Synchros in the Graveyard or your Synchrons if needed. -Mirror Force: Another protection card, and one you'll want to save for when your opponent REALLY gets the upper hand. -Pinpoint Guard: This trap allows you to reuse Junk Synchron even more, and safeguards it during your opponent's battle phase. -Scrap-Iron Scarecrow: More protection, and a reusable one at that. If your opponent doesn't have much to deal with Spells or Traps, this will be a HUGE headache for them. -Spirit Force: Ask for more protection? Here you go! Not only that, but this card will also help bring Junk Synchron back from the grave.  -Chevalier de Fleur: Your one monster that grants you the ability to negate spell/trap activation, this card and Road Warrior will specifically require Level Eater to use it's effect on Quickdraw, so it's a little difficult to bring out, but not impossible, and very strong when brought out. -Colossal Fighter: This is an AMAZING Synchro for this deck, as it will allow to bring out destroyed Warriors if it gets destroyed itself, and it also gains extra attack based on the amount of Warrior-type monsters are in your graveyard.(there will be quite a bit) -Drill Warrior: This guy here, just like Chevalier and Road, will specifically need Quickdraw + Level Eater, but for a different reason, obviously. This card is great for bringing back your Synchrons from the grave due to it's effect. -Junk Berserker: This card is extremely powerful and can punish your opponent for playing a bit too aggressively. In this deck you can lower a monster's attack by 1300, 1500, 1800, 2300, 2600, and 2700 due to it's effect. Then to make it even scarier, it also punishes defensive play since it instantly destroys defense position monsters you attack with it. -Junk Destroyer: You'll generally want to bring him out with multiple non-tuners to take full advantage of his effect. Destroying high attack monsters and pesky traps/spells is the goal with him. -Junk Gardna: This card can be swapped with whatever you deem fit, but I have it here as a simple defensive pick. Making sure you don't get field wiped by a Mirror Force if you see it coming for example. -Junk Warrior: Probably the most common thing you'll be summoning with Junk Synchron. It's not the most powerful trick up this deck's sleeve, but when executed correctly, you can have him with over 3000 attack. -Nitro Warrior: This card is very fun when you get it out early and use it in conjunction with your spells, as it will gain 1000 attack and be able to attack twice if your opponent has a second monster in face-up defense position. So it's somewhat situational, but it has a high attack stat and isn't a bad card to bring out at all. -Road Warrior: If you can bring this guy out quickly, do it! You can even add an extra of him and bring in Road Synchron if you want, as you can continually pull out monsters for Junk/Quickdraw to Synchro summon with. -Stardust Dragon: This card is more or less your insurance card. You should generally always bring it out if you're expecting cards like Dark Hole, Raigeki, Mirror Force, etc... to come into play. -Turbo Warrior: Probably the most situational Synchro in the deck, but if you're expecting to go up against other Synchro cards, you'll be glad you brought him

deck_excerpt: Endymion, Zefra, Guardragon, Magician hybrid.  Extremely consistent and ends on 4.0 disruptions in an average. This combo deck doesn't lose to Mystic
deck_description:
Explanation of every card below but here you can see this deck in action > https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOzjmxi0eac   Main deck
  • 3x Servant of Endymion - the deck ratios are molded around this card. At 3 spell counters it special summons itself and any other card which can hold counters (Typically jackal so that your plays are safe from handtraps
  • 3x Spell power control - searches Searvant or Sorcerrer Supreme. This card by itself puts 3 spell counters on your spell counter collectors
  • 3x Magical abdcutor - this is the second best spellcounter holder in game. Searches any pendulum by removing 3 spellcounters
  • 1x Mythical Beast Jackal - just 1, its a 60 card deck you prob won't banish it of desires and if you do Sorcerrer Supreme is a great target anyway
  • 1x Endymion the Mighty Master of Magic - your other "negate target" of Servant, it has many other good effects but its mainly a high scale and negate
  • 1x Cerberus - Overlaps with spellcounter gainers but you need him as a removal toolbox of Servant and a turbo card extender for climbing sometimes
  • 3x Pot of desires - if you banish a one off just use the other engine.. the deck has so many engines and routes you can't banish em all. Its a draw 2 + spellcounter
  • 3x Zefra providence - ll easly help you put 3 spell counters. Searches  Zefraath or Oracle of Zefra
  • 1x Oracle of Zefra - 2 counters, can lock your opponent of field spells with set rotation
  • 1x Zefraath - becomes a scale 7 by putting a monster in the extradeck which you ll use to facilitate a negate
  • 1x Zefraniu - searches a Zefra divine strike. Can't be used as a scale but if you draw him he is a negate if you can pend summon him and ll be able to
  • 1x zefra divine strike - Counter trap which Negates by banishing a zefra monster from the extradeck
  • 2x Terraforming - since Oracle of zefra is 2 counters this card puts 3 spell counters ;). Can also search Dragon ravine
  • 1x Set rotation - play more if unlimited.
  • 2x Dragon ravine - 3 fieldspells is enough for fieldspell searchers
  • 2x Dragon shrine - I already have many Destrudo, darkwurm senders
  • 1x foolish burial - just another shrine which isn't called shrine tbh. Boi thats a lot of darkwurms
  • 2x darkwurm - you almost never scale this card, you either discard it, normal/pend it or foolish it. He is a key for Guadragon plays - best card in the deck
  • 1x Gate 0 - surprisingly the monster effect is viable because you can summon moonlight rose and later enter hieratic link. Good scale
  • 1x Destrudo - helps with guardragon climb
  • 1x Aether the evil Empowering dragon - Summon it off hieratic link, good removal going second to
  • 1x Odd - eyes revolution dragon - So I am technically playing 3 darkwurm and 2 Aether. can be replaced by an upstart since this is TCG
  • 3X Chronograph - Do I have to explain a free monster drop? Your field doesn't even have to be empty, if you already used him use cerberus
  • 1x Timegazer - I like Chronograph..
  • 2x Tune magician - no wait this is the most important card in a deck. Playing 8 actually. He is 2 monsters and a great scale
  • 1x Dragoncaller Magician - yeah so magicians secretly always wanted to be dragons
  • 1x Violet poison - good going second card, outs floodgates. Magicians are here for the scales mostly. I used wisdom eye in the vid tho
  • 1x Oafdragon - he can plus and unlike wisdom eye he doesn't overlap with Pend call
  • 1x Dragonpit Magician - Expert in clearing mine fields, outs floodgates
  • 1x Dragonpulse - destroys problematic monsters or atleast baits em.
  • 3x Duelist allience - guess how many counters this puts on your spell counter collectors + searches pend call which is ;))))))
  • 3x Pendcall - 6 is a lot but eh discard the multiples.
  • 1x Archfiend eccentrick - to out cards such as rivarly, gozen, there can only be one off Electrumite ;)
  • 2x Curtain raiser - you don't need more then 2 curtains with dragons peeking so often ;)
  • 1x Phantazmay - genericaly decent + sometimes summoned of guardragons since you want to keep Aether in the deck
  • 1x veiler - good handtraps this format, you can afford to main few handtraps the deck is optimized everywhere else so that you can
  • 1x droll - searchable by abductor just like veiler but how often ll that come up...
  • 1x ash - tuner, good level, good handtrap
 
  • Electrumite - needs no explanation
  • Beat Cop - you need another card with arrows for pendulum summon
  • Zefra Metaltron - you often bridge into him with zefraniu, Arrows, link climbing
  • Saryuja - needed for a combo as he is a card with generic requirements yet a dragon often summoned with just 2 monsters
  • Three Burst blast dragon - stops floating and look above
  • Agarpain - summons hot red dragon archfiend abyss
  • Elpy of the guardragon - summons destrudo for more link climbing
  • Hieratic seal of celestial spheres - 2 distruptions in 1 Key card - triggers if sphere moded (Normaly summoned using agarpain + elpy)
  • Odd eyes absolute dragon -  best way of climbing into guardragons is with this card because then you get vortex
  • Vortex - Immense negate and removal going second often summoned of agarpain to
  • Deity of Tenyi - new card a monster negate + a mini borrelsword can be swapped out with omega in tcg
  • Moonlight rose dragon - it being a dragon matters. This deck spams lvl 7 synchros
  • Yazi - Cannot be targeted - removal can summon the zefraniu so no mare mare
  • Dawn dragster - because destrudo is such a fair card you often end on this card
  • Hot red dragon archfiend abyss - again summoned of agarpain can also revive tuners
Reccomended side deck
  • 2x Cerberus and 1x Garuda - since you are already maining the third cerberus you get 4 more cards which out mystic mine along with other 9
  • Xiangke Magician - a great magician but only vs light matchups which are rare but still super accessible once sided.
  • Amorphage sloth - think of it as siding artifact scythe except hieratic link or electrumite can always access it
  • 3x Sphere mode - the deck rarely normal summons
  • 3x red reboot - blow out
  • 3x Lancea - counters orcust and thunderdragon
  • 1x Droll - droll stomps some matchups so why not.

This deck aims at breaking the board and does best by going second. It makes use of the enemy's card to fuel your game and is unstoppable once well launched. Has a varying 60% win ratio in meta depending on your skill, and (almost) never loses against non-meta decks.

All Traps can be searched with Lilith

Darkest Diabolos is the best target to discard

  • Dogoran on opponent's field + Super Polymerisation (don't use Dogoran) > Starving Venom 5800 ATK

deck_excerpt: 3 combos for Sky Strikers in a single deck.
deck_description:
3 Strategies for Sky Striker combos in a single deck:
  • Sky Striker Ace - Hayate and Mystic Mine combo: block your opponent's monsters and their effects while you attack directly each turn.
  • Link Summon Borrelsword Dragon in one turn: Don't normal summon any monster in your turn and have at least one card in your hand, also, your opponent must not have a monster on one of the zones above any of the Extra Monster's Zone; using Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones, summon a Token, sacrifice the token to Link Summon Sky Striker Ace - Kagari and recover Hornet Drones from the GY; summon the token again and now sacrifice Kagari and the Token to Link Summon Knightmare Phoenix or Cerberus, sacrifice it to Link Summon Knightmare Mermaid; discard a card to use Mermaid's effect and special summon Knightmare Corruptor Ibble, sacrifice her to Link Summon the second Mermaid; special summon Ibble in your opponent's zone directly above the Extra Monster's Zone; sacrifice both mermaids to Link Summon Akashic Magician pointing Ibble to recover her; now Normal Summon Ibble and use her effect to Link Summon the Knightmare monster you summoned at the beginning of the combo; now you have 3 effect monsters and two of them are Link-2, now you can Link Summon Borrelsword Dragon, or anyother monsters you want.
  • Taking advantage of Phantom Skyblaster's effect to create tokens, fill your field with the neccessary monsters to summon the link monsters you need. if you use Hornet Drones to summon the token and then Phantom Skyblaster, you'll have 4 monsters in your Main Monster's Zone.

deck_excerpt: A dragon deck based on special summoning from the graveyard. Also has powerful XYZs.
deck_description:
The deck is based on special summoning monsters from the graveyard quickly by sending them to the graveyard. So we have two main functions of this deck here: "Send to the GY" and "Special Summon from the GY". Cards that send monsters to the graveyard (from the deck or hand):
  • Paladin of Felgrand: You can equip a high level dragon from your deck to it; when it leaves from the field, that monster is sent to the graveyard as well. So this card send a monster to the gy indirectly.
  • Morphing Jar: It discards your entire hand.
  • Dragon Ravine: You can send up to 2 monsters to the gy per turn as 1 from each your hand (cost) and deck (second effect).
  • Dragon Shrine: Up to 2 dragons to the gy.
  • Foolish Burial: 1 monster.
  • Twin Twisters: You can use its cost to send a monster to the gy.
  • Trade-In: 1 dragon.
Cards that special summon monsters: (from the hand)
  • Paladin of Felgrand
  • Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon
  • Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon
  • Kidmodo Dragon
(from the graveyard)
  • Arkbrave Dragon
  • Divine Dragon Lord Felgrand: by destroying a monster by battle.
  • Paladin of Felgrand
  • Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon: by destroying a monster by battle.
  • Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon: 1 ss per turn.
  • Decoy Dragon
  • Monster Reborn
  • Return of the Dragon Lords
  Tips To get rid of a monster your oppenent controls:
  • You can special summon Felgrand from the graveyard so that you can banish that monster, also it has its atk and def increased. This works for also getting rid of a monster in your oppenent's gy that repatedly turns back to the field.
  • You can tribute summon Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon (can use a high level monster or keeper of the shrine to summon easier) so that you can destroy that monster, also inflict effect damage to your opponent.
To get rid of spell/trap cards your oppenent controls:
  • You can special summon Arkbrave Dragon if the cards are face-up. Also Arkbrave Dragon gains attack and defence.
  • You can summon Dragon Spirit of White.
  • Also you have twin twisters.
  *If you control any monster, you can use Paladin of Felgrand's effect to special summon a dragon from your deck. *To special summon a monster that in your hand or deck, you can send both it and Arkbrave Dragon to the gy so that you can summon it in your oppenent's turn. *If you have a high level monster in your hand and Dragon Ravine, discard that monster and send Arkbrave Dragon from your deck to the gy, then special summon that monster. *Dragon Spirit of White is treated as normal monster in the gy. So you can send it from the deck to the gy by Dragon Shrine to send one more card. *You can use Foolish Burial to send Kidmodo Dragon if you want special summon from your hand, or to send Arkbrave Dragon if you want to special summon from your graveyard. *Use Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon to summon Full Armor Photon Dragon or Dark Matter Dragon. You can also use Dark Matter's effect to send dragons to the gy. *You can use Arkbrave Dragons to summon Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon, and Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon to summon Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon. *You can use side deck to create different variations of this deck.

deck_excerpt: Taken from Reddit, the most Glass Cannon deck ever constructed.  All monsters, almost all tuners.  Get out your Shooting Star Dragon and feel safe dra
deck_description: Step 1: Make Needlefiber, bring out O-Lion.  Step 2: Use Needlefiber & O-Lion to make Equimax, O-Lion triggers and gives you a Token.  Step 3: Use Equimax to make Magius.  Step 4: Use the Token to make Link Spider, which triggers Magius to search Draco.  Step 5: Use Magius & Link Spider to make Spatha.  Step 6: Summon Draco under Spatha, then use Draco to make Elpy.  Step 7: Spatha moves Elpy to the zone to the right of her.  Step 8: Elpy summons out Influencer Dragon, and use its effect to turn Spatha into a Dragon-type.  Step 9: Use Spatha & Influencer to make Agarpain.  Step 10: Agarpain brings out Shooting Star Dragon.  (Step 11:) Use Agarpain & Elpy to make Triple Burst Dragon.

deck_excerpt: Casual Gravekeeper's deck using only Gravekeeper's monsters in the main deck.
deck_description: It's a very simple yet fun Gravekeeper's deck. It's not the most effective variant, admittedly, but I love the archetype and wanted to make a deck using only Gravekeeper's as main deck monsters.  The general strategy is to get Visionary and Supernaturalist on the board as fast as you can in order to secure a strong board presence. This is usually done with Dark Renewal on a throw-away like Recruiter, or using Spiritualist through either Monster Reborn, Headman, Throne, or anything in-between. There is also a good line-up of Xyz and Link monsters that help in a win more or comeback situation, like Lightning and Skull Dread.  The most obscure choices are just personal preferences I have either due to nostalgia or just generally liking the card. I can swear to you right now that if a deck has at least 2 level 4 monsters in it, you can be damn sure I'm going to put Cowboy in my extra deck. Always.  The side deck is mainly just for the hell of it. Mind Crush, Seven Tools, and Dark Bribe are favorites from my early days of Yugioh and I love using them as Side Deck filler. It is a casual deck after all.
